<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01015e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01015e">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01015e"> 15(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Isolde of Britt &mdash; Pen / &mdash; &mdash; white hands &mdash; Calypso</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Matthew Arnold]</font> let himself be seduced by the yet more pathetic though less necessary figure of Tristram&apos;s wife, <mark>Isolt of Brittany</mark> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> and he uses her as symbol of his reflection upon this tragic tale <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Only with the last line of the third part <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> is this reflection brought completely into the light. When &ldquo;Isolt of the <mark>Snow-white Hand</mark>,&rdquo; having told her children the story of Merlin and Vivian, explains it with the words &mdash; / &ldquo;For she was passing weary of his love.&rdquo; <small> T. Sturge Moore, <a name="TSMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TSMS"><cite title="source">&ldquo;The Story of Tristram and Isolt in Modern Poetry&rdquo;</cite></a> in <cite a>The Criterion</cite></a>, I.1 (Oct 1922) 39</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05101e" href="c05all.htm#c05101e">VI.C.05:101(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
